The only things I’d still look at are these:

1. The interface change is real and potentially disruptive

Your dry-run says it will do this:

nmcli connection modify ens160 +ipv4.addresses 192.168.109.10/24
nmcli connection up ens160

That means a real deploy will add 192.168.109.10/24 to ens160 and bounce/reload that NetworkManager connection.

That is probably what you want for a lab VM, but it is the highest-risk step. If you are connected through that same interface, it could briefly disconnect you. Since you are on console/VMware, it is probably okay.

2. I want to verify the NFS exports file behavior

The dry-run shows ownership, mode, NFS services, exportfs -rav, firewall, and playbooks.

But I don’t clearly see a line saying it would create/update:

/etc/exports.d/aerolit-bundle.exports

That may just be because the output is wrapped or already exists, but I would check before running real deploy:

ls -l /etc/exports.d/aerolit-bundle.exports || true
cat /etc/exports.d/aerolit-bundle.exports || true

Expected content should be something close to:

/opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle 192.168.109.0/24(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)

If that file does not exist and dry-run is not saying it would create it, then we need to fix deploy_server.py before running the real deploy.

3. The old generated file is handled now

You moved this out:

aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml

Good. Active group_vars/all should now only have the new server-generated file, plus your normal user/default files.

Check:

ls -l /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all

You want to see:

aerolitctl_server_generated.yml
user_account.yml
workstation_defaults.yml

and not:

aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml

What I’d run next

Run these three checks:

cat /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolitctl_server_generated.yml
ls -l /etc/exports.d/aerolit-bundle.exports || true
cat /etc/exports.d/aerolit-bundle.exports || true
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run --skip-interface

The --skip-interface dry-run is useful because it tests the rest of the deployment path without the NetworkManager IP change. If that looks clean, then I’d feel pretty good about the deployment logic.

One small CLI thing still exists: --verbose has to go before the command right now:

aerolitctl --verbose status

not:

aerolitctl status --verbose

That is annoying, but not a deploy blocker.